user.priming_text: Mini Greenhouse – Line the inside with plastic wrap and cut out a window on top to create a small greenhouse for starting seeds.    Imaginative Playhouse – With some markers and scissors, a cardboard box can transform into a castle, spaceship, or even a puppet theater for children. user.priming_text: I have faced difficulties all throughout life, but I have overcame them also. Earlier this year I was homeless, living with someone that I did not care to live with because there was no housing in the area that I was living(due to an unforseen circumstances that happened last year, I sold my stuff to help out a family member and found out that they wanted me to do that so that I would have hardship). I kept talking with family members, they didn't want me living with them because they claim that they didn't have room for me and so I moved in with a friend. He was a nasty type of person and I am a clean person and we had some conflict. But, I talked to a guy that my dad works with, he owns and rents houses and he talked to me and let me move into one of his trailers, to rent. He has worked with me with the rent issues and wants to see me do better and so every month I show him some improvement and he seems to be pleased. I am happy because I am no longer homeless.
education: Associate degree in college - Occupational/vocational program

user.priming_text: I'm worried I'm never going to find my life partner. I've been single most of my adult life and have little experience in relationships. user.priming_text: Recently, I’ve felt stretched thin balancing tight work deadlines with family commitments. Unclear priorities keep shifting, so I’m context-switching all day and worrying I’ll miss something critical. Rising costs have made budgeting stressful, and a minor but persistent family health issue adds background anxiety. I’m also concerned about privacy and security news of breaches makes me second-guess what I share online. Sleep has been inconsistent, which hurts focus and makes small problems feel bigger. I’m trying to set firmer boundaries, plan deeper work blocks, and ask for help sooner, but I still worry about disappointing people and burning out.

merged_text: ['{"turn_id": 1, "sender": "3it4hwfn", "text": "My mother in law passed away two weeks ago and my husband has been shutting down", "timestamp": 32.092}', '{"turn_id": 1, "sender": "dt6h0zyo", "text": "I\'m so sorry to hear that. This was all before he met me. Drugs and drinking is such a struggle but I\'m glad he\'s improving and he needs to focus on that", "timestamp": 274.079}', '{"turn_id": 4, "sender": "3it4hwfn", "text": "I used to force him to go to family things now I do not. It was before his mom died that I relised he was better when he wasnt around his family. we started going to church, we made friends, we leaned on our hown family and friends", "timestamp": 275.701}', '{"turn_id": 4, "sender": "dt6h0zyo", "text": "Yes you\'re creating your own family unit with love and appreciation for his progress and healing", "timestamp": 300.022}', '{"turn_id": 5, "sender": "3it4hwfn", "text": "Yes I think creating our own family unit is important.\\nI think at one point it becomes about your own family\\nOur son also has moved 4 hours from home to go to collage", "timestamp": 350.454}', '{"turn_id": 5, "sender": "dt6h0zyo", "text": "Yes exactly because thats your day to day", "timestamp": 399.651}', '{"turn_id": 6, "sender": "3it4hwfn", "text": "That sure is.", "timestamp": 432.07}', '{"turn_id": 6, "sender": "dt6h0zyo", "text": "And thats hard being a empty nester. I see my mom go through that with the kids out of the house and then my dad passing away. user.priming_text: Really, the biggest difficulty I have faced recently is figuring out the correct balance between managing my mental health disorder and actually working on a freelance capacity, that doesn't put too much strain on my system physically and mentally. I experienced severe burnout back in 2023 and have spent two years recovering, but financially I can't continue to stay out of the workforce if I'm going to be able to properly take care of myself and my kid. I can't work for a company, though, because the demands that come with working with larger employers are definitely still too much for my system at present. I'm working on it, but it's a process that is taking a hell of a lot more time than I thought it would.

user.priming_text: It sounds like you’re going through a difficult time, and it's completely normal to feel overwhelmed when juggling multiple responsibilities and uncertainties. Here are a few suggestions that might help you manage your stress:    1. Prioritize and Organize: Make a list of your tasks and deadlines. Prioritizing what's urgent or important can help you focus on one thing at a time.    2. Set Boundaries: It’s essential to carve out time for yourself. Make sure to set boundaries between work and personal life to give yourself time to recharge.    3.  Practice Mindfulness: Engaging in mindfulness or meditation can help ground you and reduce stress. Even a few minutes a day can make a difference.    4. Communicate: Don't hesitate to reach out to your friends or family about how you’re feeling. Sharing your concerns can strengthen your relationships and provide you with support.    5.  Take Breaks: Make sure you take regular breaks during work to clear your head. Short walks or stretching can make a big difference in your focus and energy levels.    6.  Plan for the Future: While it’s natural to worry about uncertainty, try to focus on what you can control. Setting small, achievable goals for the future can help you feel more secure.    7. Seek Support: If feelings of stress or uncertainty persist, consider talking to a professional. They can offer strategies tailored to your situation.
education: Master's degree (e.g., MA, MS, MEng, MEd, MSW, MBA)
